data.content:
In .NET 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the EF Core Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The provider is now async-only — no configuration flag can re-enable synchronous execution.

**What throws at runtime:**

Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw an `InvalidOperationException`:

> Synchronous I/O is not supported by the Cosmos DB provider. Use the corresponding async method instead.

**Fix — convert to async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| .NET 10 | .NET 11 |
|---------|---------|
| Sync works with opt-in (`EnableSynchronousIO()`) | Opt-in removed; throws unconditionally |
| `ToList()` / `First()` / `Count()` allowed | Must use `ToListAsync()` / `FirstAsync()` / `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` allowed | Must use `SaveChangesAsync()` |

This also means callers up the stack must go async (`async Task<T>` all the way up), so plan for the change to ripple through controllers/services.
